body:
When a programmer writes some wrong code such as the following array as a right value without index:
If the array is a one-bit array such following line, it would not report error message at lint time and it would not cause C++ code to compile error.
```
 valids [i] <= valids; // no warning and no error when compile c++ code
```
However, if the array is vector array such as the following line, it would not report error message too. But it could cause compile error.
```
data_array[i] <= data_array; // no warning at lint time and there are some errors in compile c++ code
```
Compile error message would be the following messages:
```
...
Vtest.cpp:874:27: error: invalid array assignment                                                                            
                 = vlTOPp->test__DOT__data_array;                                                                            
                           ^~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~                                                                             
Vtest.cpp:888:45: error: invalid conversion from ‘CData* {aka unsigned char*}’ to ‘CData {aka unsigned char}’ [-fpermissive] 
         vlTOPp->test__DOT__data_array[0U] = __Vdlyvval__test__DOT__data_array__v257;
...
```
I think it is not clear for the programmer to understand which line in RTL code produces such error messages. We can only try to feel it out from C++ Compile error.
Icarus verilog  will produce error messages in the above case like:
```
test.v:23: error: Array valids needs an array index here.
test.v:33: error: Array data_array needs an array index here.
```


The following is a full code for testing this feature.
```
module test(
    input clk,
    input rst,
    input [7:0] addr,
    input we,
    output [7:0] data
);

reg [7:0] data_array [0:255];
reg valids[0:255];

integer i;

always@(posedge clk)
    if (rst)
        for (i = 0 ; i < 256 ; i = i + 1)
            valids [i] <= 0;
    else if (we)
        valids [addr] <= 1;
    else
        for (i = 0 ; i < 256 ; i = i + 1)
            valids [i] <= valids; // no warning and no error when compile c++ code

always@(posedge clk)
    if (rst)
        for(i = 0 ; i < 256 ; i = i + 1)
            data_array[i] <= 0;
    else if (we)
        data_array[addr] <= 1;
    else
        for (i = 0 ; i < 256 ; i = i + 1)
            data_array[i] <= data_array; // no warning at lint time and there are some errors in compile c++ code


assign data = data_array[addr];

endmodule
```
